    <h2 id="beginning">In the beginning … </h2>
    <p>FreeCEN started as <em>The Devon 1891 Census project</em>. This was initiated [?begun] and planned largely by John&#160;Lerwill (for more information, see this <a href="https://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/DEV/Census.1891">GenUKI page</a>). One of the other main instigators [?founders — to replace 'main instigators'] was Brian&#160;Randell (GenUKI, Devon; and Newcastle&#160;University), with considerable support from the late Bob&#160;Muchamore in Australia. The late Roy&#160;Conibear (d. 2001) in Canada also gave considerable aid to the Devon Project. The 1891 Devon transcription was instigated [?set up] as a pilot project.</p>
    
    <h2 id="expansion">Expansion …</h2>
    <p>Devon was followed in mid-2000 by the 1891 Cornwall transcription which was undertaken as the <a href="https://sites.rootsweb.com/~kayhin/ukocp.html">Cornwall Online Transcription Project</a> in partnership with the <a href="https://www.opc-cornwall.org/">Cornwall Online Parish Clerks</a>. Kay&#160;Hinnrichsen of Australia and Michael&#160;McCormick in Cornwall led the project. Their team completed the project [?task] in 2008, having transcribed all the Cornish 19th century census returns.</p>
    <p>By the end of 2000, we had set up four other counties, and more followed. Bob took over General Coordination of the project in August, 2001. Brenda&#160;Bowers joined the project as Coordinator for Nottinghamshire about one month after.</p>
    <p>Brenda then took on the role of helping anyone with queries, working alongside Bob&#160;Muchamore. With the introduction of Microsoft&#160;XP® and Bob only having Windows&#160;32® he had difficulty helping some volunteers so they shared the issues.</p>
    
    <h2 id="movingOn">Moving on …</h2>
    <p>After the death of Bob&#160;Muchamore in 2004, Dave&#160;Newbury took over as chair, and Brenda became the Assistant Chair. When Dave became seriously ill, in 2008, Brenda took over as Chair. This was envisioned [?first seen] as a temporary appointment, but sadly Dave passed away two years later, and Brenda continued as chair for over a decade.</p>
      <p>Early in the development of the organisation, we appointed separate Heads for Scotland and Wales, reflecting the differences in censuses in those countries.</p>
      <p>Although started as an independent project, FreeCEN always worked closely with FreeBMD, and it was a natural move to become a project [?part] of FreeBMD the charity. FreeBMD the charity was then renamed to be <em>Free UK Genealogy</em>, reflecting that it did far more than FreeBMD the project. FreeBMD Trustee David&#160;Mayall was responsible for liaison with the trustees, and for technical aspects of the development of FreeCEN.</p>
        <p>The Trustees of FreeBMD (as it then was) worked with the Church of Latter Day Saints (the LDS or Mormons). We remember Geoffrey&#160;D.&#160;Mawlam, Area Manager (Europe North) for The Genealogical Society of Utah with gratitude for his help with this. The LDS sent the FreeCEN management the 1891 census on microfiche, which were [??was] passed on to the Coordinators (known as Coords).</p> 
   
    <h2 id="earlyDays">The early days of transcribing for FreeCEN</h2>
    <p>To be a transcriber at the start of the project, you needed access to a microfiche reader. Some transcribers already had one or they bought one themselves. For Nottinghamshire, one of Brenda’s  helpers took on the role of going round to lots of business and libraries to collect redundant fiche readers. Other coordinators were able to do the same.</p>
      <p>Second-hand car dealers proved to be a great source of second-hand microfiche readers. In those days, the dealerships were sent information about available vehicles on fiche — when this was computerised, the fiche and their readers were no longer needed, and many dealerships passed their readers on to FreeCEN. Volunteers then had to deliver them to the transcribers. Those who did <em>not</em> have access to a microfiche reader had to use the one at the local library or Archives, often going once or twice a week. They took a blank sheet with them and wrote out the census by hand. On returning home they then typed it up. They kept repeating that until they finished the piece. This could be a Herculean task as a census piece can have from about 150 images to over 500 images. Each image has 30 people on a page. Transcribers also had to have a computer with a floppy disc drive (or an external drive).</p> 
    <p>Once the transcriber had access to a microfiche reader, the coordinator then had to post the microfiche to them. The transcriptions were copied onto a floppy disk, which was returned, also by post, to the coordinator together with returning the microfiche. A few had an internet account, and would email the transcriptions.</p>
    <p>The Coordinator then posted the CD and the fiche on to a Checker (who again had to have a PC with a floppy disc drive). To see what needed to be checked, and to proofread the spreadsheet, the checkers used a tool called <em>CSVCHECK</em> written by Peter&#160;Cox. Peter was unable to update it when Windows<sup>®</sup> came in, so sent the programme to Brenda, and Brenda’s son updated it to the version that was in use until the early <mark>something missing</mark> </p>
    <p>Some microfiche got lost in the post. To stop this happening, and so that people did not have to use microfiche, volunteer Kevin&#160;Howell (of FreeBMD) was appointed the charity’s first digitiser. Brenda recalled all the images from the Coords (from all over the world). Some were sent directly to Kevin, others to her, together with a list of the fiche which had gone missing. He copied the images from microfiche to CD or DVD.  Kevin then posted the CDs to the Coords and a copy to Brenda. This exercise took more than a year, and after his death was taken over long-term on a self-employed basis by Kevin’s daughter Stacey. The work is continued today by FreeUKGenealogy employee Helen&#160;Bainbridge, who also sources new images for transcription.</p> 

    <h2 id="quality">Ensuring the quality of transcriptions</h2>
    <p>The final stage of quality control for the FreeCEN data is validation. These are the instructions from 2004 [?add ', as they appeared']:</p>
    <div class="island island--light">
      <p>“The County Co-ordinator (or his appointed delegate) will clear queries passed back by checkers. The output file from this process will be passed to the Database Maintainer, and will be scanned for acceptability before formatting an upload file for the on-line database loading. The upload file will be in Comma-Separated-Values ascii file format.</p>
      <p class="note">“PLEASE NOTE: If you have started validation using VALCENS you must complete the validation using VALCENS. If you need a replacement for the VALCENS routine as you are part way through a piece, please request through the helpers mailing list.</p>
      <p>[should this paragraph also be in red?] “NOTE that because of the manner in which the program operates, it is of considerable advantage to use a PC with a minimum 400MHZ processor and recent hard-drive.” </p>
    </div>

    <p><mark>word missing — ?Contact</mark> was renewed with the LDS, and they sent us CDs for 1841, 1851, 1861, and 1871 so that transcription could begin [should that be continue?] [?add 'for those years'].</p>

    <h2 id="goingLive">Going live!</h2>
    <p>In July 2003, the FreeCEN website went live. The online database facilities [?functions] were developed by Dave&#160;Mayall of the core FreeCEN technical team and Trustee of Free UK Genealogy, and Stuart&#160;Morgan. The website notes that the initial year’s 150 volunteers had doubled in 12 months, and in four years had reached 500 transcribers.</p>
    <p>By April of 2006 the website had been revamped, including a new logo. We then had 2,000 transcribers.</p>

