    <h2 id="findingMore" class="clear--left">Finding more censuses to transcribe</h2>
    <p>Because of problems we were having with getting access to the 1891 Census, Trustee Dave&#160;Mayall and FreeCEN Manager Dave&#160;Newbury were in contact with  Archive CD books (ACDB) to provide us with images on CD instead. They started with the 1861 Census. Archive CD Books [link?] was the brainchild of Rod&#160;Neep.</p> 

    <figure class="bq">
      <blockquote>The Archive CD Books Project exists to make reproductions of old books, documents and maps available on CD to genealogists and historians, and to co-operate with libraries, museums and record offices in providing money to renovate old books in their collection, and to donate books to their collections, where they will be preserved for future generations.</blockquote> 
      <figcaption>ACDB website, 2019</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p><mark>something missing or wrong</mark> Contact  ordered by and sent to a Coord who was also a member of the church, which continued for some time until the LDS decided for economics reason to stop supplying any more CDs or DVDs to any organisation around the world.</p>
    <p>Some local record offices worked with us to transcribe their county, for example the Devon and Cornwall Archives services. This enabled FreeCEN to begin transcribing their county.</p> 
    <p>In 2019, the LDS very kindly gave us the microfiche from the Nottingham Family History Centre which was closing down. This gave us the fiche for counties from 1891 which were never with us in the first place, and for missing Pieces from otherwise completed counties.</p>  

    <h2 id="transforming">Transforming the FreeCEN website (and more)</h2>
    <p>In the early 2010s the Trustees of Free UK Genealogy decided to update their three websites (FreeBMD, FreeCEN and FreeREG), and commissioned a suite of designs for them. Implementation started with FreeREG, which needed the work most urgently, and had a willing and able computer programmer in Kirk&#160;Dawson of Canada. He was able to guide and to a large extent implement the developments. The new FreeREG website went live in 2017.</p>
    <p>The transformation of FreeREG was far larger than a simple re-design of the website — it included moving the database to a new structure and an examination of the behind-the-scenes processes of transcription and validation. Kirk’s changes lead to improvements in the quality of the transcriptions, the experience of the volunteers and the services for users.</p> 
    <p>Kirk and Ben&#160;Brumfield (a contracted developer) then switched their skills to the service of FreeCEN. The FreeCEN Committee and the development team planned a series of developments [?improvements] (in seven phases) that saw the database moving to the new system, the new website going live, and the original transcription tools being replaced with ones that would produce files that could be loaded into the new database. [split sentence?]</p>
      <p>Much of the systems development and associated data management tasks was — and continues to be — undertaken by volunteers: Geoff&#160;Jarvis in Australia, Anne&#160;(Ruby Developer), and other coordinators and new volunteers with a special interest in data. Their work underpins a radical change to how we validate records, and how we organise place information. In FreeCEN1, places were simply in counties, but in FreeCEN2, we now have places in a full location hierarchy, including latitude and longitude.</p>
      <p> We are now working through the records created on the original FreeCEN transcription validation software. This is taking a long time as the process slows the search considerably, so we can do this for only a short time each night (UK time) when there are fewer users who do not see any difference to their search times.</p>  
    <p>The outcome of the work of Geoff and his team is that we will be able to allow you to search by place of birth!</p> 

    <h2 id="recent">Recent history</h2>
    <p>In 2022 Brenda stood down as Chair. For many years the Chairs had been supported by a committee which included the Scotland and Wales Coordinators, and others with skills needed to run the project, but this had struggled to meet, and the Covid-19 restrictions prevented it from continuing. A new FreeCEN committee was formed, with a different structure: Helen&#160;Bainbridge is Chair and Secretary for the monthly meetings, and committee members have responsibility for specific areas.  These areas include Scotland, Wales, geographical data, and technical forward planning and execution. We plan that a Free UK Genealogy Trustee will lead the committee in future.</p>
    <p>On the completion of the development of the new FreeCEN (excluding place of birth) Kirk stood down as a volunteer, and new (or new-to-FreeCEN) technical volunteers have taken over the work of continuing to improve your access to free, high quality transcriptions of the UK’s census data.</p>

    <h2 id="acknowledgements">Acknowledgements</h2>
    <p>Some of this history was told to Brenda&#160;Bowers by Bob&#160;Muchamore, who was General Coordinator of the project from 2001. Some is the personal recollection of Pat&#160;Reynolds, former Director of Free UK Genealogy. Part of this history has been gleaned from the historic snapshots of the FreeCEN website which are preserved by the <em>Internet Archive</em> on its ‘Wayback’ machine.</p>

